      { q: 'Assess whether the UK\'s current account deficit is sustainable in the long run.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Arguments it is sustainable: The deficit is financed by willing foreign investors attracted to UK assets, indicating market confidence. The UK\'s position as a financial centre generates invisible earnings. As long as capital inflows continue, the arithmetic is sustainable. Service exports partially offset goods deficits. Arguments it is not sustainable: The persistent structural nature (post-deindustrialisation) suggests fundamental competitiveness problems. Reliance on foreign capital creates vulnerability to sentiment shifts. Net investment income has turned negative as foreign ownership of UK assets grows. A sudden capital withdrawal could force painful adjustment through sharp depreciation and austerity. Evaluation: Sustainability depends on maintaining foreign investor confidence and whether the deficit reflects productive investment or unsustainable consumption. Structural reforms to boost export capacity and productivity would reduce long-term risks.' }
