      { q: 'Evaluate the view that monetary policy is more effective than fiscal policy for managing the UK economy.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Arguments for monetary policy: Greater flexibility - the MPC can change rates quickly in response to data. Political independence reduces short-term political interference. Can be adjusted monthly versus annual budgets. Avoids crowding out effects of government borrowing. Arguments for fiscal policy: More direct impact on aggregate demand (especially government spending). More effective in a liquidity trap when interest rates are at the lower bound. Can be targeted at specific sectors or regions. Automatic stabilisers provide immediate counter-cyclical support. Limitations of monetary policy: Transmission mechanism is slow and uncertain. Ineffective at zero lower bound. Distributional effects may worsen inequality (QE inflates asset prices). Arguments against fiscal policy: Political/implementation lags. Risk of crowding out. Budget constraints limit scope. Evaluation: Neither is universally superior. The optimal approach depends on economic circumstances: monetary policy for normal demand management, fiscal policy for severe downturns or when monetary policy is exhausted. In practice, coordination between both provides the most effective policy mix.' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which austerity was an appropriate response to the UK\'s fiscal position after 2010.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: 'Arguments for austerity: The deficit exceeded 10% of GDP, risking credit rating downgrades and rising borrowing costs. Reducing the deficit maintained market confidence and avoided a potential debt crisis (as seen in Greece). Spending cuts signalled fiscal discipline and helped anchor inflation expectations. Long-term, sustainable public finances are necessary for future policy flexibility. Arguments against: Premature austerity during a fragile recovery risked a double-dip recession through the negative multiplier. The deficit was largely cyclical and would have reduced with growth. Cutting spending reduced demand when the private sector was also deleveraging. Infrastructure and human capital cuts reduce future productive capacity. International evidence suggests multipliers are larger during recessions, magnifying the contractionary effect. Evaluation: Timing was arguably premature - the recovery was not yet self-sustaining. A more gradual consolidation profile, combined with infrastructure investment, might have achieved fiscal sustainability with less damage to growth and public services.' }
